  "text": "To monitor endothelial injury in vivo, we used our new molecular imaging approach [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] designed for early diagnosis [CITATION_3] and use in mechanistic studies to monitor the retinal microvessels. [CITATION_4] Imaging probes were generated by conjugating the binding ligands of endothelial ICAM-1 onto the surfaces of injectable fluorescent microspheres. These α-ICAM-1 or control probes were then injected into the bloodstreams of normal and diabetic animals. Accumulation of the firmly adhering probes in vivo was visualized using SLO [ Figure 3a ]. Firmly adhering probes were visible as bright dots in the fundus images of the examined eyes [ Figure 3b ]. The number of α-ICAM-1 and IgG-conjugated probes, which were used as negative controls, did not differ significantly between diabetic and normal rats. However, a significantly higher number of α-ICAM-1 probes adhered to the retinal vessels of the diabetic rats than those in normal controls [ Figure 3c ]. A significant difference in adhesion of α-ICAM-1 probes was also observed between normal ",
